excerpt: An 18th-century arch bridge over a 120m chasm, with an interpretive center in a guardhouse.
detail_description: Puente Nuevo, or New Bridge, is a remarkable 18th-century arch bridge that spans a 120-meter chasm in Ronda. It connects the modern part of the city to the historic center and offers stunning views of the River Guadalevin. The bridge is part of a walking tour that includes other significant landmarks such as El Mercadillo and La Ciudad. Despite its name, Puente Nuevo is not actually new; it was completed between 1759 and 1793.
name: Puente Nuevo. Centro de Interpretación
address: Pl. España, s/n, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Storied palace featuring a water mine & hanging gardens that can be explored by visitors.
detail_description: La Casa del Rey Moro is a historic palace with a fascinating water mine and hanging gardens that are open for exploration by visitors. Carved into the cliffs of El Tajos gorge, this site dates back to the Moorish era when protecting water supplies was crucial during constant wars in Al-Andalus. The Ronda's Water Mine, built in the 14th century, showcases medieval Islamic engineering and is a unique marvel in Spain. Nearby attractions include St.
name: La Casa del Rey Moro
address: C. Cta. de Santo Domingo, 9, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Mosque turned Catholic church with ornamental Renaissance & Baroque-style features & a viewing deck.
detail_description: Iglesia de Santa María la Mayor is a former mosque turned Catholic church located in Plaza Duquesa, one of the favorite squares in Andalucia. The church features ornamental Renaissance and Baroque-style elements and offers a viewing deck with stunning panoramic views. The building has a rich history, with layers of construction from different periods including Visigoth, Moorish, and Roman influences.
name: Iglesia de Santa María la Mayor
address: Pl. Duquesa de Parcent, S/N, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Popular 1800s park featuring tree-lined promenades & panoramic balconies suspended over a cliff.
detail_description: Alameda del Tajo, located in Ronda, Spain, is a picturesque 19th-century park known for its stunning panoramic views of the Sierra de Grazalema mountains, El Tajo gorge, and Guadalevin River. The park features tree-lined promenades with lush greenery including pine and oak trees. Visitors can take leisurely strolls along the main avenue leading to cliff-edge balconies offering breathtaking vistas.
name: Alameda del Tajo
address: C. Virgen de la Paz, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Excavated 13th-century bathhouse featuring rooms, vaults & portions of the water system.
detail_description: The Arab Baths Archaeological Site, also known as Banos Arabes, is a well-preserved 13th-century bathhouse located in the San Miguel neighborhood of Ronda. The baths were supplied with water from the Las Culebras stream through a sophisticated Moorish water system. The complex includes cold, warm, and hot bathing rooms, with the central room featuring horseshoe arches and barrel-vaulted ceilings adorned with star-shaped skylights.
name: Arab Baths Archaeological Site
address: C. Molino de Alarcón, s/n, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Jardines De Cuenca is a stunning terraced garden situated on the ledges of the embankment along the Guadalevin river gorge in Ronda. The gardens feature a picturesque winding staircase leading from the city's edge down into the lush greenery, offering breathtaking views of the gorge and its iconic bridge. Visitors can enjoy panoramic vistas from various vantage points, including a small garden viewpoint with an excellent perspective of Puente Nuevo.
name: Jardines De Cuenca

excerpt: Public museum housed in a 14th-century home with gardens, courtyards, balconies & water features.
detail_description: Mondragon Palace is a historical gem in Ronda, serving as a public museum within a 14th-century residence. The palace features captivating gardens, courtyards, balconies, and water features. It offers exhibitions that delve into the local settlements and the extensive history of Ronda from prehistoric times to various eras such as Paleolithic, neolithic, Roman, Moorish, and Christian periods.
name: Mondragon Palace
address: Pl. Mondragón, s/n, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Ronda is a mountaintop city in Spain’s Malaga province that’s set dramatically above a deep gorge. This gorge (El Tajo) separates the city’s circa-15th-century new town from its old town, dating to Moorish rule. Puente Nuevo, a stone bridge spanning the gorge, has a lookout offering views. New town’s Plaza de Toros, a legendary 18th-century bullring, is one of the city’s most recognizable landmarks.
detail_description: Ronda is a captivating mountaintop city in Spain's Malaga province, boasting a striking location above a deep gorge known as El Tajo. The city is divided into the old town, dating back to Moorish rule, and the new town from the 15th century. The iconic Puente Nuevo bridge spans the gorge and offers breathtaking views. Ronda hosts significant events like the holy week processions, showcasing religious fervor and impressive floats carried through the streets by devoted locals.
name: Ronda

excerpt: Private collection of historic weapons, clocks, scientific instruments & witchcraft-related items.
detail_description: Museo Lara is a unique museum located near Puente Nuevo, offering an extensive private collection of historical artifacts. Housed in a traditional townhouse, the museum features a diverse range of items including historic weapons, clocks, scientific instruments, and witchcraft-related pieces. Visitors can explore gory torture weapons, swords, and peculiar witchcraft artifacts alongside other historical objects. The museum provides an ideal setting for a family visit and takes about an hour to tour.
name: Museo Lara

detail_description: Puente Viejo, a charming 17th-century stone bridge in Ronda, is a hidden gem offering stunning views of the town. It is situated at a lower elevation than the more well-known New Bridge and provides picturesque vistas of Ronda perched on the cliff top.
name: Puente Viejo

detail_description: Casa Museo Don Bosco, located in Old Ronda, Calle Tenorio, is a modernist mansion built at the beginning of the 20th century. Originally owned by a wealthy family, it was later donated to the Salesian Order and now serves as a shelter for elderly and sick priests of the order.
name: Casa Museo Don Bosco

detail_description: Plaza del Socorro is a bustling square located in the heart of the new part of Ronda. It's a popular spot for leisurely strolls and people-watching due to its central location, drawing in a steady stream of pedestrians. The 12th-century Church of Socorro graces one side of the plaza, adding to its charm. Surrounded by historic buildings, cozy terraces, and quaint stores, it also features a striking statue of Hercules and lions.
name: Plaza del Socorro de Andalucía
address: Pl. del Socorro, 9, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Square featuring tapas bars & a fountain with a statue of Hercules & 2 lions, symbol of Andalusia.
detail_description: Pl. del Socorro is a charming square in Andalusia, known for its tapas bars and a beautiful fountain adorned with a statue of Hercules and two lions, which are symbolic of the region. Nearby, on Calle Lorenzo Borrego, you can find Pizza Michelangelo, a cozy restaurant offering delicious food like Tagliatelle Michelangelo with mushrooms, ham, tomato and cream as well as Pizza Lucia with chicken, ham, mozzarella and more.
name: Pl. del Socorro

excerpt: Vistas of the gorge, mountains and Puente Nuevo can be seen from this scenic viewpoint.
detail_description: Mirador de Ronda is a popular viewpoint in the old town of Ronda, offering stunning vistas of the gorge, mountains, and Puente Nuevo. Visitors can relax on seats at three small balconies while admiring the impressive views of the old town and the Church of Santa Maria La Mayor. The viewpoint is named after renowned architect Jose Martin de Aldehuela and provides a perfect vantage point to take in the surrounding countryside.
name: Mirador de Ronda
address: Ctra. de los Molinos, 1955, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Deep, dramatic gorge dividing the city, with a bridge joining the 2 sides & a viewing platform.
detail_description: El Tajo de Ronda is an iconic Spanish city known for its location straddling the El Tajo Gorge and as the birthplace of bullfighting. The former Moorish bastion has attracted famous visitors like Ernest Hemingway and Orson Welles, offering adventurous vistas and picturesque narrow streets. The town is divided by a hundred-meter-deep gorge, crossed by the historic Puente Nuevo bridge built in the 18th century.
name: El Tajo de Ronda

excerpt: Steps to a viewpoint over a dramatic gorge spanned by an arched bridge built in the 18th century.
detail_description: Located high up in the mountains overlooking Ronda, the Mirador Puente Nuevo de Ronda provides stunning views over the bridge spanning the gorge below. If you only have time for a short trip, this is definitely the spot to see it.
name: Puente Nuevo de Ronda viewpoint

excerpt: Arched stone gate dating to the 13th century, giving entry to a historic walled enclosure.
detail_description: Puerta de Almocábar is a 13th-century arched stone gate that served as the prominent entrance to the historic walled enclosure of Ronda. It was built during Muslim rule and features three successive doors and two semicircular towers that once housed guards. The name 'Al-maqabir' refers to a former cemetery located nearby.
name: Puerta del Almocábar
address: Pl. Ruedo Alameda, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Museum of bullfighting in an 18th-century bullring associated with legendary matador Pedro Romero.
detail_description: The Bullring of the Royal Cavalry of Ronda is a historic 18th-century bullring associated with legendary matador Pedro Romero. Located in the heart of Ronda, it is one of the oldest bullfighting arenas still in use and represents an important aspect of Andalusian and Spanish culture. The Corrida Goyesca show, held between late August and early September, attracts numerous visitors.
name: Bullring of the Royal Cavalry of Ronda
address: C. Virgen de la Paz, 15, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Mirador de Aldehuela is a must-visit spot in Ronda, offering stunning views of the Puente Viejo, Jardines de Cuenca, and the Serrania de Ronda. The footpath starting at Plaza de Maria Auxiliadora leads to several viewing areas, including Mirador Puente Nuevo de Ronda and Mirador del Viento. A little path from the mirador takes you down into the gorge where you can enjoy breathtaking views towards the bridge.
name: Mirador de Aldehuela

detail_description: Arco de Felipe V is a significant landmark in Ronda, hastily constructed after the collapse of the Arab Gate in 1742. It is named after King Felipe V, known for his efforts to rebuild Spain's economy during the War of Succession. The arch marks an entrance to the city and features a unique trapezoidal pinnacle above its opening. Situated near Puente Viejo, it offers picturesque views and stands as a testament to Ronda's historical legacy.
name: Arco de Felipe V

detail_description: Pl. Duquesa de Parcent, located in the heart of the Old Town, is a truly breathtaking square surrounded by magnificent architecture.
name: Pl. Duquesa de Parcent

detail_description: Guadalevín River flows through the city of Ronda, carving a deep canyon that divides it. The sheer walls of the canyon drop over 100 meters to the river below, with white stone buildings perched on its edge. Three bridges, including the Roman Bridge (Puente Viejo), Arab Bridge (Puente San Miguel), and New Bridge (Puente Nuevo) connect the two parts of the city.
name: Guadalevín

excerpt: Charming 16th-century pedestrian bridge with expansive views of the city & surrounding landscape.
detail_description: Puente Viejo, also known as the Old Bridge, is a charming 16th-century pedestrian bridge in Ronda. It offers expansive views of the city and surrounding landscape. The bridge is located at a lower altitude than the famous Puente Nuevo, providing great views of Ronda from below. Visitors can reach Puente Viejo by walking through the Jardines de Cuenca or taking a road in the old town past Casa del Rey Moro.
name: Puente Viejo

detail_description: The Minaret of San Sebastian, also known as St. Sebastian's Minaret, is a historic site located on Plaza de Abul Beka in Ronda. This 14th-century minaret is the only remaining structure from Ronda's original mosques and stands as a reminder of the city's Islamic past.
name: Minaret of San Sebastian
address: Pl. Abul Beka, s/n, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Plaza Duquesa de Parcent is a charming and peaceful square located in the historic center of Ronda. It is renowned for its tranquil atmosphere, adorned with traditional buildings featuring characteristic balconies. The square offers a green space shaded by numerous trees, providing an authentic and cozy ambiance. Visitors can relax on benches while listening to the soothing sound of running water from the fountain.
name: Plaza Duquesa de Parcent
address: Pl. Duquesa de Parcent, 11, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Carrera Espinel is a charming pedestrian street adorned with vibrant lanterns, creating a lively and festive ambiance, especially at night. The bustling atmosphere of the new town ensures that the area remains vibrant well into the late hours, making it an ideal spot for those who enjoy being amidst crowds and reveling in a lively party scene.
name: Carrera Espinel

excerpt: Deep, dramatic gorge dividing the city, with a bridge joining the 2 sides & a viewing platform.
detail_description: Ronda is a town located in the depths of Malaga Province, perched atop bluffs and surrounded by the Sierra de Grazalema and Sierra de las Nieves. It boasts historical landmarks such as arched Roman bridges, arabesque architecture, and the oldest bullring in Spain.
name: El Tajo de Ronda

detail_description: In Ronda, a picturesque town with many attractions, the Iglesia del Espíritu Santo stands out as one of its most emblematic landmarks. This church was built by the Catholic Monarchs on the site of a former mosque and holds historical significance. Visitors can explore various exhibitions featuring religious artifacts dating back to the 18th century and enjoy panoramic views by climbing the bell tower for a small fee. The church also hosts regular masses and is known for its simple yet popular religious services.
name: Iglesia del Espíritu Santo
address: C. Espíritu Santo, 15, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Balcón del Coño, located in Ronda, Andalusia, is a must-visit spot for breathtaking views of the El Tajo gorge. The footpath starting at Plaza de Maria Auxiliadora leads to several viewing areas, including Mirador Puente Nuevo de Ronda and Mirador del Viento. The most famous area is the Balcón del Coño, which juts out over the gorge and offers a great photo opportunity.
name: Balcón del Coño
address: P.º Blas Infante, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Small museum with works by the Spanish Cubist painter Joaquín Peinado, who was born in Ronda.
detail_description: The Unicaja Joaquín Peinado Museum, located in Ronda's Old Town, is a small yet captivating museum showcasing the works of Spanish Cubist painter Joaquín Peinado. The museum features an impressive collection of Picasso's etchings and ceramics, along with a permanent display of Peinado's neo-cubist art.
name: Unicaja Joaquín Peinado Museum
address: Pl. del Gigante, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: The Parroquia de Nuestra Señora del Socorro, located near Plaza del Socorro, is a charming 20th-century church with a rich history. The original structure was built in the 18th century but was destroyed during the Spanish Civil War. The current church features an impressive Baroque facade and beautiful interiors. Visitors can also climb the bell tower for a stunning panoramic view of the city.
name: Parroquia de Nuestra Señora del Socorro
address: Pl. del Socorro, 15, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Local & global fare such as burgers, meat dishes, pasta & desserts are served at this low-key venue.
detail_description: Restaurante Las Maravillas is a charming eatery situated in the heart of Ronda, offering a diverse menu featuring local and international cuisine such as burgers, meat dishes, pasta, and delectable desserts. The restaurant boasts an inviting ambiance with superb decor and is renowned for its Andalusian specialties along with an impressive selection of wines. It's a great spot to indulge in tapas and savor quality wine while immersing yourself in the culinary delights of southern Spain.
name: Restaurante Las Maravillas

detail_description: Mirador La Hoya Del Tajo is a must-visit viewpoint in Ronda, Spain. It offers breathtaking views of the town, its rural surroundings, and the impressive Hoya del Tajo gorge. Visitors can also spot ancient watermill ruins that once harnessed the power of the downhill torrent before being destroyed.
name: Mirador La Hoya Del Tajo
address: Ctra. de los Molinos, 1955, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Classic Spanish food & wine is served in a traditional environment at this established venue.
detail_description: El Lechuguita is a well-established venue in Ronda, Malaga, offering classic Spanish food and wine in a traditional setting. It is renowned for its legendary and surprisingly affordable dining experience. Despite the variety of dining options in Ronda, El Lechuguita stands out as a must-visit destination for those seeking an authentic taste of Spanish cuisine. Whether it's the affordable prices or the traditional environment, this restaurant has garnered praise from locals and visitors alike.
name: El Lechuguita
address: C. Virgen de los Remedios, 35, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

excerpt: Creative takes on tapas, from squid sandwiches to pork ears, in a sleek, industrial-chic space.
detail_description: Tragatá is a modern and stylish restaurant in Ronda, known for its creative take on traditional Spanish dishes. The menu offers a variety of tapas options that combine local flavors with global influences, such as squid sandwiches and pork ears.
name: Tragatá | Benito Gómez | Restaurante en Ronda

detail_description: Restaurante Casa María, located in Ronda, Malaga, is a top-rated dining spot known for its ever-changing menu crafted from the freshest produce available each day. With over 3,000 five-star reviews on TripAdvisor, this restaurant offers innovative and authentic dishes served by Maria and her family. Guests can enjoy a simplified dining experience with no menu to decipher; instead, they are treated to 5-6 well-proportioned courses of delicious dishes paired with local wines.
name: Restaurante Casa María
address: Pl. Ruedo Alameda, 27, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Pl. de María Auxiliadora is a charming park located at the edge of the old town, offering breathtaking views of the surrounding countryside. Visitors can enjoy the serene atmosphere and may even be serenaded by a musician playing piano under the shade of an orange tree. It's a perfect spot to immerse yourself in nature and soak in the beauty of the area.
name: Pl. de María Auxiliadora

detail_description: Tabanco Los Arcos is a charming wine bar located beneath the arches of an ancient mansion in Ronda. It offers a rustic and cozy tavern-style atmosphere where visitors can enjoy a selection of local wines from the surrounding Serrania vineyards. The bar is conveniently situated near the old town and provides a perfect opportunity to sample Ronda wines while taking in breathtaking views of the gorge and bridge.
name: Tabanco Los Arcos

excerpt: This preserved Nasrid Dynasty house displays classic Islamic architecture & a central courtyard.
detail_description: Casa del Gigante, located on Plaza del Gigante, is a well-preserved Nasrid palace dating back to the 14th and 15th centuries. This historic house showcases classic Islamic architecture with a central courtyard. The palace offers insights into Ronda's history, from its geological formation to the Moorish urban development that shaped the city. The interior features an impressive indoor patio, while the Phoenician stone sculpture in the courtyard adds to its charm. Nearby attractions include St.
name: Casa del Gigante
address: Pl. del Gigante, 1, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: El Tajo Canyon in Ronda is a breathtaking natural wonder that splits the city in half with its steep 120-meter-deep gorge carved by the Guadalevin River. Visitors can admire this spectacular sight from the Puente Nuevo bridge, which offers stunning views of the canyon and an appreciation for its architectural feat. For a more immersive experience, adventurous travelers can trek down to the bottom of the canyon from Plaza Maria Auxiliodora and gaze up at the town towering above.
name: El Tajo Canyon

detail_description: The Ronda Tourist Office, located by the bull ring at Plaza de Toros, is a must-visit for anyone exploring the city. The English-speaking staff are friendly and eager to provide you with the latest information on events such as concerts and exhibitions. They also offer tourist tickets. Visitors have praised the office for its excellent service and competent answers to their questions.
name: Ronda Tourist office
address: P.º Blas Infante, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: The Puente Romano, also known as the Roman Bridge, is a 16th century bridge over the gorge in Ronda. It is a beautiful structure with great views of the river below. The bridge is slippery when wet and may be dangerous to walk on when wet, so be careful if you visit.
name: Puente Romano

detail_description: Eleven years ago, I visited the Ruinas de la Alcazaba castle, which is a truly stunning place. Despite some warmth in October, it captivated me with its beauty. Although undergoing slight reconstruction at that time, what I witnessed in 2010 left me in awe. The cultural diversity oozing from this location is remarkable and highly recommendable. Warm greetings to all who visit this magnificent site!
name: Ruinas de la Alcazaba

detail_description: Bardal is a renowned restaurant located in Ronda, a charming town perched on the edges of a dramatic gorge in Andalusia. The restaurant offers an outstanding and unique menu that pays homage to classic roots with dishes like boneless quail stuffed with white sausage, guinea fowl breast with brioche, milk and foie gras, accompanied by black sausage and truffle sauce.
name: Bardal | Benito Gómez | Restaurante en Ronda
address: C. José Aparicio, 1, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Paseo de Blas Infante is a charming pedestrian boulevard in Ronda, Spain. It offers a pleasant tree-lined walk with plenty of shade, running parallel to the Ronda pit and passing through parks. The boulevard ends at the National Parador and features several viewpoints that offer spectacular views of the valley. Along the way, visitors can admire the oldest bullring in Spain and take in the landscape formed by the river Guadalevin.
name: Paseo de Blas Infante
address: P.º Blas Infante, 1, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Located in the western area of the city, Mirador del Viento is a viewpoint that offers stunning views of Ronda's hillside, from smooth hills to cultivated fields. Although it may have been challenging to reach in the past, visitors find it worth the effort. The viewpoint provides an impressive perspective of the bridge and offers a scenic and romantic walk.
name: Mirador del viento

detail_description: The Mirador de los Viajeros Románticos, also known as the Romantic Travelers Viewpoint, is a charming spot in Ronda that offers a unique photo opportunity. The colorful tiles on the wall depict a side view of Ronda city and tell the story of travelers who have visited throughout the centuries. This 19th-century complex has captured the hearts of tourists with its romantic ambiance and historical significance.
name: Mirador de los Viajeros Románticos

detail_description: Iglesia de Padre Jesús is a Gothic church located in the Padre Jesus neighborhood of Ronda, near the Murallas de Levante. It is believed to have been built between the 15th and 16th centuries and was dedicated to Saint Cecilia. The church houses revered images such as Nuestro Padre Jesus Nazareno and Maria Santisima de los Dolores, which are processed every Holy Thursday.
name: Iglesia de Padre Jesús

excerpt: Elevated classics pair with wines & craft cocktails in this polished, charming venue with a bar.
detail_description: Nestled in the charming outskirts of Ronda's new town, Restaurante Tropicana is a delightful gem that promises an unforgettable dining experience. This family-run establishment radiates warmth and hospitality, making it a welcoming spot for both locals and visitors alike. The restaurant boasts a modern tapas menu that showcases an impressive array of dishes crafted from high-quality organic meats, fresh seafood, and vibrant produce. Each plate is not only delicious but also visually stunning, reflecting the culinary expertise behind its creation.
name: Restaurante Tropicana
address: C. Virgen de los Dolores, 11, 29400 Ronda, Málaga, Spain

detail_description: Ctra. de los Molinos is a picturesque road that winds through stunning countryside, offering breathtaking views of rolling hills and charming windmills. The route is lined with vibrant wildflowers and offers plenty of opportunities for peaceful walks and scenic drives. Travelers can immerse themselves in the natural beauty of the area while enjoying the tranquility of the surroundings. Along Ctra. de los Molinos, visitors can also discover quaint villages where they can experience the local culture and savor traditional cuisine.
name: Ctra. de los Molinos
